    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from SpaceX\'s S-1 prospectus, here is a structured summary of information regarding Starlink\'s network capacity, performance metrics, and growth plans.\n\n### **Current Network Capacity & Scale (as of March 31, 2026)**\n*   **Constellation Size:** Approximately 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO), representing about 75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit.\n*   **Cumulative Downlink Capacity:** The constellation supports over 700 Tbps of cumulative downlink capacity.\n*   **Subscribers:** Approximately 10.3 million Starlink Subscribers across 164 countries, territories, and markets.\n*   **Mobile Users:** Approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices using satellite-to-mobile services across ~30 countries.\n\n### **Per-Satellite Throughput & Technology**\n*   **Current Satellites:** The majority of the constellation consists of second-generation, higher-throughput **V2 Mini satellites**.\n*   **Next-Generation (V3) Satellites:** Scheduled to begin deployment in the second half of 2026, each V3 satellite is designed to offer **1 Tbps (1,000 Gbps) of downlink capacity**.\n*   **Deployment Efficiency:** A single Starship launch will be capable of deploying up to **60 V3 satellites**, representing a potential **twenty-fold increase in downlink capacity deployed per launch** compared to a Falcon 9 launch.\n\n### **Performance Metrics (Quality of Service)**\n*   **Latency:** Median latency of approximately **25 milliseconds**.\n*   **Download Speed:** Provides "fiber-like" download speeds at a median of **225 Mbps during peak hours** for residential users. The technology is capable of providing speeds exceeding **400 Mbps** with round-trip latencies as low as **21 milliseconds**.\n*   **Coverage:** The service has the technological capability to provide connectivity everywhere on Earth, including the poles.\n\n### **Congestion Management & Bandwidth Per User**\n*   The documents do not detail specific congestion management protocols or hard caps on bandwidth per user. Instead, they emphasize that **increasing the total capacity of the constellation** is the primary method for supporting more customers and improving service during peak periods.\n*   **Average Revenue Per User (ARPU):** Monthly Starlink Subscriber ARPU decreased from **$91 in 2024** to **$81 in 2025**, and from **$86 in Q1 2025** to **$66 in Q1 2026**. This decline is attributed to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced plans. The company expects this trend to continue but be offset by scale and cost reductions.\n\n### **Utilization Rates & Network Load**\n*   Specific utilization rates or current network load percentages are not provided. The focus is on **installed capacity**.\n*   A key metric for the AI segment is **"Nameplate Compute Draw,"** which reached **1.0 gigawatt** as of March 2026. This metric measures installed GPU power draw in data centers and is separate from satellite network utilization.\n\n### **Planned Capacity Growth & Expansion Plans**\n1.  **Constellation Expansion:**\n    *   Continue deploying **V2 Mini satellites**.\n    *   Begin deploying **next-generation V3 satellites** (1 Tbps each) using Starship in H2 2026.\n2.  **Mobile Constellation (Starlink Mobile Gen2):**\n    *   Expanding from ~650 dedicated **V1 Mobile satellites**.\n    *   Plan to deploy **next-generation V2 Mobile satellites in 2027**.\n    *   Spectrum acquisition from EchoStar (65 MHz in the US, plus global MSS licenses) expected to close in November 2027 to enable "orders of magnitude" increased capacity.\n3.  **Launch Vehicle:**\n    *   **Starship** is critical for the rapid and cost-effective deployment of both V3 broadband and V2 Mobile satellites, significantly increasing per-launch capacity.\n4.  **Growth Strategy:**\n    *   The goal is to **onboard new users while improving service** for existing ones by materially increasing constellation capacity.\n    *   For mobile services, the aim is to "substantially reducing mobile \'dead zones\' worldwide" with future 5G connectivity to unmodified phones.\n\n### **Enterprise & Government Capacity**\n*   **Enterprise Solutions:** Provide high-speed, low-latency, and reliable internet for businesses across various industries (aviation, maritime, etc.). Contracts are based on subscriptions, data consumption, capacity, or other pricing models.\n*   **Government Solutions (Starshield):** A separate, secure satellite network for government customers, providing high-speed, resilient connectivity.\n\n**In summary,** the prospectus highlights that Starlink\'s network capacity is being aggressively scaled through next-generation satellites and Starship launches to support rapid subscriber growth, improve performance, and enter new markets (mobile broadband). Key metrics show strong current performance (speed, latency), with a strategic focus on increasing total capacity rather than disclosing granular utilization data.',
